{%- comment -%} Terms of service — for /pages/terms {%- endcomment -%}
<section class="wa-page wa-page--legal wa-section--bleed" aria-labelledby="wa-terms-title">
  <div class="wa-aurora" aria-hidden="true"><div class="wa-aurora__blob"></div></div>
  <div class="wa-grain" aria-hidden="true"></div>

  <div class="wa-container wa-page__inner">
    <div class="wa-page__hero">
      <span class="wa-eyebrow">{{ 'wa.terms.eyebrow' | t }}</span>
      <h1 id="wa-terms-title" class="wa-page__title">
        {{ 'wa.terms.title_a' | t }} <span class="wa-gradient-text">{{ 'wa.terms.title_b' | t }}</span>
      </h1>
      <p class="wa-page__lede">
        {{ 'wa.terms.lede' | t }}
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="wa-page__layout">
      <article class="wa-prose wa-page__article">

        <h2>1. The deal</h2>
        <p>
          When you purchase a Weird Artist application, you receive a
          non-exclusive, non-transferable, perpetual license to install and
          use that specific version of the application on machines you own
          or control, for personal or internal business use.
        </p>

        <h2>2. What &ldquo;perpetual&rdquo; means</h2>
        <ul>
          <li>The version you bought keeps working forever, offline, on your hardware.</li>
          <li>One year of free updates is included from the date of purchase.</li>
          <li>After that year, the app continues to work &mdash; updates simply become optional.</li>
          <li>We will never push a remote kill-switch, expiry, or forced subscription.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>3. What you may do</h2>
        <ul>
          <li>Install the app on as many of your own devices as you reasonably need.</li>
          <li>Use it for paid client work &mdash; that&rsquo;s the whole point.</li>
          <li>Keep working backups of the installer and your license key.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>4. What you may not do</h2>
        <ul>
          <li>Resell, rent, sublicense, or distribute the binaries.</li>
          <li>Reverse-engineer the protected portions, except where local law explicitly allows.</li>
          <li>Remove copyright or license notices.</li>
          <li>Use the app to do anything illegal or to harm other people&rsquo;s data.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>5. Refunds</h2>
        <p>
          30 days, no questions, no forms. See the
          <a href="/pages/refund-policy">refund policy</a>.
        </p>

        <h2>6. Updates &amp; support</h2>
        <p>
          One year of feature updates and bug fixes is included. Critical
          security fixes for known issues will be made available to all
          previous buyers regardless of update window. Email-only support
          via <a href="mailto:support@weirdartist.io">support@weirdartist.io</a>,
          two business days reply.
        </p>

        <h2>7. Source escrow</h2>
        <p>
          For tools we ship as long-term workhorses, we publish a snapshot of
          the build to a public escrow repository when a major version is
          retired or if the studio ceases operating. You buy a working tool;
          you keep a working tool.
        </p>

        <h2>8. Disclaimer of warranty</h2>
        <p>
          The software is provided &ldquo;as is,&rdquo; without warranty of
          any kind. We test thoroughly, but we cannot guarantee it will fit
          every workflow or never produce an unexpected result. Always keep
          backups of your data before running batch operations.
        </p>

        <h2>9. Limitation of liability</h2>
        <p>
          To the maximum extent permitted by law, our aggregate liability for
          any claim arising from your use of the software is capped at the
          amount you paid us in the previous 12 months. We are not liable for
          indirect, incidental or consequential damages.
        </p>

        <h2>10. Governing law</h2>
        <p>
          These terms are governed by the laws of the jurisdiction in which
          Weird Artist is registered. Disputes will first be addressed in
          good faith over email; failing that, by the competent courts of
          that jurisdiction.
        </p>

        <h2>11. Changes</h2>
        <p>
          We may update these terms for new releases. The version that
